{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4b71f0cd-9c76-4250-84b2-8e633b767d3c","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` stops the page from adding inset padding, but there are two other common culprits:\n\n1. **Shell/NavigationPage chrome** — the toolbar still reserves space at the top.\n2. **System bar backgrounds** — on Android the bars may have a translucent scrim, making it look like content doesn't extend underneath.\n\nHere's the full recipe for a true edge-to-edge photo viewer in .NET 10 MAUI:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"\n             Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\">\n\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           VerticalOptions=\"Fill\"\n           HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n           IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nKey pieces you may be missing:\n\n| What | Why |\n|------|-----|\n| `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` | Removes the Shell toolbar that eats top space |\n| `NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"` | Same thing if you're using `NavigationPage` instead of Shell |\n| `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the view | Lets the view itself extend into inset regions (belt-and-suspenders with `SafeAreaEdges`) |\n\n**Android – make system bars transparent** (in `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs` or your style):\n\n```csharp\n#if ANDROID\nWindow.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\nWindow.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n#endif\n```\n\nOr in `Platforms/Android/Resources/values/styles.xml`:\n\n```xml\n<item name=\"android:statusBarColor\">@android:color/transparent</item>\n<item name=\"android:navigationBarColor\">@android:color/transparent</item>\n```\n\nIn .NET 10 Android already defaults to edge-to-edge layout, but the scrim colors can still make it *look* padded if they aren't transparent.\n\n**TL;DR** — You likely need to hide the nav bar chrome (`Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"`) and set transparent system-bar colors on Android. `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` alone isn't enough.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"caf66848-7fc3-4d30-8293-d6025b29903d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10, specifically wanting an image to fill the entire screen behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a question about .NET MAUI's edge-to-edge/full-screen display APIs. In .NET 10 (which is still in preview as of my knowledge), there have been changes to how edge-to-edge content is handled, particularly on Android where edge-to-edge became the default starting with Android 15.\n\n\nThe main properties to consider are `SafeAreaEdges` on the Page to control which edges respect safe area insets, and `IgnoreSafeArea` on individual views to bypass those insets entirely. On Android with .NET 10, apps default to edge-to-edge rendering following Android 15's behavior.\n\nBut I'm realizing that just setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` might not be enough—the system bars themselves need to be transparent for content to actually display behind them, otherwise the content will still be blocked even if it's technically allowed to extend into that space. On Android, the system bars default to edge-to-edge but might still have a background scrim, so I need to explicitly set the status and navigation bar colors to transparent. On iOS, `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` alone isn't enough—I should also consider `IgnoreSafeArea` on the view itself. The real solution for .NET 10 MAUI involves making sure the system bars are transparent so content renders behind them, and if there's a Shell or NavigationPage wrapping things, I need to handle that chrome separately. I'm realizing the core issue is likely a combination of hiding the navigation UI and making the system bars transparent, so I need to provide practical solutions covering both the XAML configuration and the platform-specific setup required to achieve that full-bleed effect.","outputTokens":1800,"requestId":"5019:19764A:1BF38B4:1F1E0A0:69FA92F3"},"id":"22214aef-baa9-4836-8029-ea88e4241cd7","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:02:12.318Z","parentId":"8e27c452-d203-4af0-be60-f605dadd163a"}
